In this attempt, I perform random filtering of the datasets. Recall that the class sizes are unbalanced, and that some images were of poor quality. My hope is that this filtering will reduce some of the noise in the dataset.

After some experimentation, I found the best results were with a relatively simple convolutional neural network. Meaning that I didn't use ResNet for the backbone, nor imagenet to inialise the weights. I'm using online image augmentation. The final layer contains no activation function, and we want to apply L2 normalisation so that the embeddings are in Euclidean space.

In [18]:
from tensorflow.keras.applications.resnet import ResNet50
base_model = ResNet50(include_top=False, pooling='avg', weights='imagenet', input_shape=(DIM,DIM,CHANNELS))
base_model.trainable = True

model = tf.keras.Sequential([
    tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=2, padding='same', activation='relu', input_shape=(DIM,DIM,CHANNELS)),
    tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),
    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.5),
    tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=2, padding='same', activation='relu'),
    tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2),
    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.5),
    tf.keras.layers.Flatten(),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(256, activation=None), # No activation on final dense layer
    tf.keras.layers.Lambda(lambda x: tf.math.l2_normalize(x, axis=1)) # L2 normalize embeddings

])

We load the dataset, visualise the classes, and apply both pre-fetching and caching for performance.

In [34]:
batch_size=128

def build_data(data_dir, batch_size):
  train_dataset = tf.keras.preprocessing.image_dataset_from_directory(
      data_dir,
      labels="inferred",
      label_mode="int",
      class_names=None,
      color_mode="rgb",
      batch_size=batch_size,
      image_size=(DIM, DIM),
      shuffle=True,
      seed=SEED,
      validation_split=VAL_PROP,
      subset="training",
      interpolation="bilinear",
      follow_links=False,
  )

  val_dataset = tf.keras.preprocessing.image_dataset_from_directory(
      data_dir,
      labels="inferred",
      label_mode="int",
      class_names=None,
      color_mode="rgb",
      batch_size=batch_size,
      image_size=(DIM, DIM),
      shuffle=True,
      seed=SEED,
      validation_split=VAL_PROP,
      subset="validation",
      follow_links=False,
  )

  test_dataset = tf.keras.preprocessing.image_dataset_from_directory(
      test_dir,
      labels="inferred",
      label_mode="int",
      color_mode="rgb",
      # batch_size=batch_size,
      image_size=(DIM, DIM),
      shuffle=True,
      seed=SEED,
  )
  return train_dataset, val_dataset, test_dataset

def prefetch_data(data_dir, batch_size):
  train_dataset, val_dataset, test_dataset = build_data(data_dir, batch_size)
  train_dataset = train_dataset.cache().prefetch(buffer_size=tf.data.AUTOTUNE)
  val_dataset = val_dataset.cache().prefetch(buffer_size=tf.data.AUTOTUNE)
  test_dataset = test_dataset.cache().prefetch(buffer_size=tf.data.AUTOTUNE)
  return train_dataset, val_dataset, test_dataset

train_dataset, val_dataset, test_dataset = build_data(train_dir, batch_size)

We first perform online learning with triplet hard loss and a soft margin of 1. The Adamax compiler is used, as it can apparently improve performance for networks that deal with embeddings.

In [37]:
def scheduler(epoch, lr):
  if epoch < 10:
    return lr
  else:
    return lr * tf.math.exp(-0.1)
In [38]:
model.compile(
  optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adamax(),
  loss=tfa.losses.TripletHardLoss(1, soft = True),
)
In [39]:
history = model.fit(
  train_dataset,
  validation_data = val_dataset,
  epochs = 50,
  callbacks = [
    tf.keras.callbacks.LearningRateScheduler(scheduler),            
    tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', mode='min', restore_best_weights = True, patience = 10),
    tf.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(f"{CHECKPOINT_DIR}/training_filtered_resnet_aug", monitor= 'val_loss', save_best_only = True, mode = "min", save_weights_only = True),
    tf.keras.callbacks.ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor="val_loss", factor=0.33, patience=2, mode="min", min_delta=0.0001, min_lr = 0)
  ]
)

We visualise the training results.

In [40]:
def plot_loss(history):
  epochs = len(history.history['loss'])
  loss = history.history['loss']
  val_loss = history.history['val_loss']
  epochs_range = range(epochs)
  plt.plot(epochs_range, loss, label='Training Loss')
  plt.plot(epochs_range, val_loss, label='Validation Loss')
  plt.legend(loc='upper right')
  plt.title('Training and Validation Loss')
  plt.show()

plot_loss(history)

We have quickly reached a validation loss plateau.

mapper=umap.UMAP( n_neighbors = 100, min_dist= 0.1).fit(train_embeddings, y_train)
cluster = hdbscan.HDBSCAN(
    algorithm ='best', 
    approx_min_span_tree = True,
    gen_min_span_tree = False, 
    leaf_size = 40, 
    metric='euclidean', 
    min_cluster_size = 25,
    min_samples = 25, 
    p = None
).fit(mapper.embedding_)

plt.title("Clustered UMAP visualisation of train embeddings.")
scatter = plt.scatter(
    mapper.embedding_[:, 0], 
    mapper.embedding_[:, 1],
    c = cluster.labels_,
    s = 0.1, 
)

plt.legend(
  handles = scatter.legend_elements()[0], 
  labels = pd.Series(cluster.labels_.tolist()).astype("string").sort_values().unique(),
  loc="right",
  bbox_to_anchor=(1.2, 0.5)
)
plt.xlabel("D1")
plt.ylabel("D2")
plt.show();

We can see that most of the data forms a Gaussian sphere, but that there is some divergence from the central spheroid. These divergences could be distinct individuals.

We next repeat this process with Local Outlier Factor.

In [63]:

scatter = plt.scatter(
    mapper_embeddings[:, 0], 
    mapper_embeddings[:, 1],
    c = lof_labels,
    s = 0.1, 
)

  handles = scatter.legend_elements()[0], 
  labels = pd.Series(lof_labels.tolist()).astype("string").sort_values().unique(),
  loc="right",
  bbox_to_anchor=(1.2, 0.5)
)
plt.xlabel("D1")
plt.ylabel("D2")
plt.show();

From above, we see that LOF has failed to identify outliers with the UMAP embeddings. The degree of seperation within the data isn't great enough.
